## MCP Server Best Practices

### Tool Definitions
- Clear, descriptive `name` and `description` for every tool
- Input schema with Zod or JSON Schema — validate all inputs
- Return structured results (not just strings)
- Error responses: use MCP error codes, not exceptions
- Idempotent operations where possible

### Resource Handling
- Resources for read-only data access
- Use URI templates for parameterized resources
- MIME types on all resource responses
- Pagination for large resource lists

### Server Lifecycle
- Handle `initialize` properly — declare capabilities
- Graceful shutdown on process signals
- Connection keep-alive for stdio transport
- Proper cleanup of resources on disconnect

### TypeScript MCP Server Pattern
```typescript
import { Server } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js";
import { StdioServerTransport } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js";

const server = new Server({
  name: "server-name",
  version: "1.0.0",
}, {
  capabilities: { tools: {}, resources: {} }
});

// Register tools
server.setRequestHandler(ListToolsRequestSchema, async () => ({
  tools: [{ name: "tool_name", description: "...", inputSchema: {...} }]
}));

server.setRequestHandler(CallToolRequestSchema, async (request) => {
  // Handle tool calls
});
```

### Python MCP Server Pattern
```python
from mcp.server import Server
from mcp.server.stdio import stdio_server

app = Server("server-name")

@app.list_tools()
async def list_tools():
    return [Tool(name="tool_name", description="...", inputSchema={...})]

@app.call_tool()
async def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict):
    # Handle tool calls
